Therefore after the tachyon condensation, two D-strings are located
at 
 
This configuration of D-strings is shown in Fig. . The
intersecting  D-strings are recombined! Naively it might have been
expected that the recombination might be difficult to be realized in Yang-Mills
theory since the locations of the D-strings are represented by the eigen
values and the recombination process must interchange two eigenvalues only
in a half of the worldvolume (). However this is possible, 
as seen in the above diagonalization, due to the gauge transformation
which was singular at  originally before the tachyon condensation 
(the limit ). So essentially the tachyon condensation
resolves the singularity of the gauge transformation and enables the
interchange of the left "halves" of the D-strings (the  region).

The intriguing point here is that the magnitude of the tachyon mode 
corresponds just to the interbrane separation. This can be easily seen
in Eq. () with . Therefore, in the D-brane recombination,
the tachyon condensation is geometrically realized. 

It is interesting to note that the condition () has
the following geometrical meaning. From the expression ()
of the transverse displacement, we observe that when the tachyon
develops the condensation and  becomes large enough,  
the D-string worldvolume embedding is "waving" in the bulk (See
Fig. ). This situation is quite strange in the naive view
of the 
energy minimization in which the D-string energy would be given mostly
as a tension times its length. The "wave" should be smeared.
The requirement that this "wave" does not appear is equivalent to the
condition that the function  () has only a single
extremum. This condition is easily evaluated as  which is
satisfied by ().


 
 
