Large intersection angle and Sen's conjecture 

In the previous section we showed that the recombination of the
intersecting D-strings is realized in Yang-Mills theory, 
the low energy scheme of string theory. However as mentioned in the
introduction, this phenomenon of recombination should be related to the
tachyon condensation of brane-antibrane system. The worldsheet picture
() tells us that when , the tachyon mass squared
reaches its lower bound  which is well-known as that
of tachyons whose condensation is conjectured to make the
brane-antibrane disappear (the Sen's conjecture, see
Ref. ).  

Then, how the disappearance of the brane-antibrane is related to the
recombination? The answer is found when we consider D-strings
intersecting at large , . For this large
, the worldvolume parametrization with  (the horizontal axis)
is not appropriate. Instead, we exchange the roles of  and  : 
now let us parametrize the worldvolume of D-strings by , the vertical
axis.(This kind of the change of the axes of the
worldvolume parametrization has been investigated in Ref.  as
"target space rotation.") 
Then the displacement of the D-strings from this axis is measured
by a scalar field  which was originally  (See the left 
of Fig. ). One notices that in this parametrization, two
D-strings become a pair of a D-string and an anti-D-string , since
the 
orientation of one D-string is reversed compared to the other, as is
obvious in Fig. .


 
 
