The tachyonic mode  of () remains at the origin and tends to
be condensed. Since we have explicitly shown in the previous section 
that the condensation of
this mode is equivalent to the D-string recombination, so assuming that 
even with large  this equivalence is maintained, the
condensation of this tachyonic mode for large  
should provide again the
recombination depicted in the right of Fig. .
Reminding of the fact that the natural parametrization of the
worldvolume is , we observe from this figure that around 
where the tachyon is localized the brane-antibrane has disappeared!
We regard this as a qualitative verification of the Sen's conjecture on
the tachyon condensation. 

The single assumption which we made in the argument above was that 
the identification of the fluctuation mode () with the 
lowest mode of the worldsheet spectrum () is valid also for large
. Although it is hard to imagine that this is violated, in the
following we provide another evidence that the identification for 
large  is valid. 

For larger , the approximation adopted in the
previous section is getting worse, and so we cannot use the Yang-Mills
approach.  Hence we necessarily have to use alternative picture mentioned
above, the worldvolume parametrization in terms of . 
This brane-antibrane picture is difficult to be analysed
since it needs stringy description with the energy scale , such
as string field theories.
